<h2>Role</h2>
<p>
  I worked closely with a product manager in the early stages to create a compelling design solution for our enterprise partner. We outlined all the different attributes for actions, triggers, and interventions. I focused more on web/desktop design framework as this was going to be mainly part of an enterprise admin tool solution initially. Design consisted of early wireframes that were shared with stakeholders, various iterations for internal reviews, and final design prototypes and assets for the partner and our engineering team.
</p>

<h2>Research</h2>
<p>
  We asked our doctors to create general Care Plans for these 4 conditions: Pregnancy, HIV, Diabetes Type II, and Hypertension. We didn’t ask them what features or functions they’d like to see. We first gathered raw data and identified the shared and distinguished characteristics of each condition. Then, we created a spec document that listed all the product and feature requirements. This document was then shared with the doctor group to make sure this covers their use cases. We went through multiple iterations and this process helped tremendously in solidifying the product and everyone’s understanding of the product vision.
</p>

<h2>Discovery</h2>
<p>Here is what we learned from our research and iterative feedback process.</p>
<p>
  Care Plans basically have 2 components: actions and triggers. Actions define “what” patient needs to do. Triggers define “when” patient does the actions. An example can be: patient must schedule a visit with their primary care provider (what) a month after they enroll in the care plan (when). Or patient must schedule a visit with a Podiatrist (what) when they experience their feet swelling(when). Triggers can be time-based or event-based.
</p>

