<h2>Design Process</h2>

<p>Here are the key decisions we made to keep the product simple and user-friendly:</p>

<p><b>Limit the number of action types to reduce complexity</b></p>
<p>We finalized on the following 5 actions types: medication, general todo, appointment, measurement, and alert.</p>

<p><b>2 types of care plans, wellness and condition-based</b></p>
<ul>
  <li>Both types are created by doctors.</li>
  <li>While wellness plans can be self-enrolled by patients, condition-based ones can only be assigned by a doctor</li>
</ul>

<p><b>Condition-based Care Plans will have at least one key metric to track</b></p>
<p>i.e. fasting blood glucose level for diabetes</p>

<p><b>Doctors will always be supplied with a generic template to start with, never from a complete scratch</b></p>
<p>
  While we strongly believe in diversifying the content, we believed that it was a bit early to have everything depend on the author. The author can always remove and create their own content but we believed it’d be great to start with some baseline template so that it’s not overwhelming or time-consuming
</p>

